{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f787424a-f811-48de-8346-fdcad39ea9af","content":"Here are the skip attributes for each framework:\n\n**MSTest**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason message\")]\n[TestMethod]\npublic void MyTest() { }\n```\n\n**xUnit**\n```csharp\n[Fact(Skip = \"Reason message\")]\npublic void MyTest() { }\n\n// or for data-driven:\n[Theory(Skip = \"Reason message\")]\npublic void MyTest(int x) { }\n```\n\n**NUnit**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason message\")]\n[Test]\npublic void MyTest() { }\n```\n\n**TUnit**\n```csharp\n[Skip(\"Reason message\")]\n[Test]\npublic void MyTest() { }\n```\n\nKey differences: xUnit uses a `Skip` **property** on the test attribute itself, while the others use a **separate** attribute placed alongside the test attribute. All four require a reason string.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ca49e31c-6b77-4798-aa68-b0e66a005e65","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the correct attributes to skip tests with a reason message in MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit. This is a straightforward knowledge question about .NET test frameworks. I have a relevant skill - `dotnet-test-frameworks` - which provides reference data for test framework patterns including skip annotations. Let me invoke it.\n\nActually, looking more carefully, the `dotnet-test-frameworks` skill description says: \"Reference data for .NET test framework detection patterns, assertion APIs, skip annotations, setup/teardown methods, and common test smell indicators across MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit.\" This is exactly what we need - it covers skip annotations.\n\n\nBut I realize this is straightforward enough that I can answer directly from my knowledge without needing to invoke the skill. The skip attributes are well-established across these frameworks.","outputTokens":524,"requestId":"9819:3A3A20:1A9211:22CC77:69FFDC0D"},"id":"ea9197f3-0edb-4124-9242-7fb9c04e75e9","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:15:06.293Z","parentId":"4bbba04e-8e60-4f1